{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511788"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:45:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:45:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11789"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11789"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.36,0.04,0.14,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102413"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4403"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84887"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"3300"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35808"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102413"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a six-month history of feeling increasingly off balance. He is concerned about falls and has also noticed his right hand has developed a resting tremor. He is struggling to initiate some movements. He has a medical history of gambling addiction. He does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with a festinating gait and increased muscle tone with resistance to passive movement. He denies any changes in mood and scores 28/30 on Mini-Mental State Examination. A diagnosis of Parkinson\u0027s Disease is made.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Levodopa monotherapy","Levodopa / benserazide","Pramipexole monotherapy","Levodopa / selegiline","Benzhexol monotherapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevodopa / benserazide\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for Parkinson\u0027s disease. Levodopa is the most commonly used drug as it is converted into dopamine in the brain and helps to relieve symptoms such as tremors, stiffness and bradykinesia. It is always administered alongside a dopa decarboxylase inhibitor such as benserazide, which prevents peripheral conversion of levodopa to dopamine. This allows a higher concentration of levodopa to cross the blood-brain barrier, resulting in a higher CNS concentration of dopamine and making it a more effective treatment than \u003Cstrong\u003Elevodopa monotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDopamine agonists such as\u003Cstrong\u003E pramipexole\u003C/strong\u003E are generally considered second-line treatment. In some cases they can be considered as first-line monotherapy, however a known side effect is increased impulsive behaviour. Given this patient\u0027s history of gambling addiction, pramipexole is inappropriate as first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe addition of \u003Cstrong\u003Eselegiline\u003C/strong\u003E, a monoamine oxidase type B (MAO-B) inhibitor, is often used as an adjunct to first and second-line therapy to manage the wearing off effect. MAO-B inhibitors prevent the breakdown of dopamine in the brain, thus increasing dopamine levels and prolonging the treatment effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnticholinergic drugs such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ebenzhexol\u003C/strong\u003E are also used as adjuncts to relieve tremors by blocking the action of acetylcholine. In Parkinson\u0027s disease, the ratio of dopamine to acetylcholine favours acetylcholine as dopamine production declines. Anticholinergics correct this imbalance which results in reduction of the tremor. However, the main side effect is worsening of cognitive impairment. Since cognitive impairment and Parkinson\u0027s disease commonly coexist, anticholinergics are used only if there is no cognitive impairment with tremor-predominant disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Levodopa is always administered alongside a dopa decarboxylase inhibitor to prevent peripheral conversion to dopamine and therefore maximise the dose of levodopa entering the CNS.","Dopamine agonists, in particular pramipexole, can increase impulsive behaviour and should be avoided in patients with a history of addiction.","Monoamine oxidase type B inhibitors prevent the breakdown of dopamine in the brain, thus increasing dopamine levels and prolonging the treatment effect."],"references":["Riederer P, Laux G. MAO-inhibitors in Parkinson\u0027s Disease. Exp Neurobiol. 2011;20(1):1-17. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3213739/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11789"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84887"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T16:03:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T16:04:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4403"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102413"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","